ok team, i'm introducing a ban system, to tackle the ongoing issues.

Why do we need a ban system, it is apparent that some miners are misbehaving while they try to trick the evaluation system. But do fail to allow the compute rentals to work, thus we're in need of a retrospective "policing/refereeing". So we're creating this ban system.

How it works:
The system is only applied once the executors are validated, and report healthy. Once such a machine has pass all the evaluations successfully and is listed as an available GPU server to be used by the network, we expect  no  apparent reason  of why a subsequent rental should fail.

So, if such a machine fails to co-operate, we assume something illegitimate is happening, in other words "misbehaviour" of the connected executor. As a result, we need to reject this machine retrospectively, since the current evals can't catch it.

The proposed in the PR ban system works like this:

- a "misbehaviour" happen when either; an executor rejects a rental request, or is serving a rental and their machine is either shut or the App/container that's running in their GPU server is killed or removed (not by user's intend)
- once 2 of  such misbehaviours happen within 1 hour you get an "offence"
- if you have only one offence within the last 7 days, this will result to an hour (1hr) of a time ban
- if there're more offences, the time ban compounds to 1h -> 2h -> 4h -> 8h -> 24h (max) based on offenses in a 7-day window
- We index the GPU UID, so you can't swap the machine to a different miner_uid
- Executors automatically become available (after re-eval) when the ban expires

Hey team, we're about to deploy 10/10/2025 9:00 AM ( Friday, October 10, 2025 9:00:00 AM ) this code change https://github.com/one-covenant/basilica/pull/179 

We're introducing incentives ramp-up for miners.

What does this mean, the ramp-up is a linear unlocking of the incentives the more you keep your node available in the network. if a GPU node gets offline for more than (about) 2hrs, then their ramp-up is rest to start.
The maximum ramp-up percentage is on the 14th day of being online.

To explain this with an example, say that you had your H100 node online for 7 days continuously, you'll be paid 50% of the incentives that would be allocated otherwise for the H100.

In addition to the availability metric, assume that a new miner joins the H100 category with 1 node, and another node already exist. As of today the incentives that correspond to the h100 category would be split to 50% to each miner, as there are only 2 nodes in this GPU category. With this update we aim to reward more the loyal miners, thus after this update, the new miner would receive 25% of the h100 and the loyal miner (assuming 14days of availability) would receive the remaining 75%.

In other words, the more available you make sure your nodes are, the better the incentives in the mid-long run.

For the miners that had already been offering the nodes these days, your availability is counted retrospectively. So if you had a node already online for 14 days, nothing changes. Also, the ramp-up is on the node, no on the miner's UID. So if a miner has been offering various nodes but the have been flicking on-off, unfortunately the ramp-up would reset based on the above rules.

Next we'll add the ramp-up percentages in grafana to see how you stack-up.

No Ops are required from miners or validators to receive this update. Big kudos to @itzlambda for the work!
